    <h2 class="date-header">Thursday, August 23, 2012</h2>

	<div class="entry-category-android entry-category-glassboard entry-author-nick_bradbury entry-type-post entry" id="entry-6a00d83451863669e20177444e5b69970d">
       <div class="entry-inner">
					<h3 class="entry-header"><a href="https://nick.typepad.com/blog/2012/08/glassboard-shines-on-nexus-7.html">Glassboard Shines on Nexus 7</a></h3>
		



		<div class="entry-content">

			<div class="entry-body">
				<p>Earlier this week I <a href="https://bit.ly/NIfwJy">announced</a> a new version of Glassboard for Android which supports <a href="https://bit.ly/PD2o9f">Glassboard premium</a>. What I didn't mention is that this new version is also optimized for tablets like the Nexus 7.</p>  <p>If you used an earlier version of Glassboard on your new tablet, chances are you were disappointed by how photos didn't resize to fill the larger display. And if your eyes are like mine, you probably squinted to read anything. You may also have noticed that scrolling wasn't as smooth as it should be.</p>  <p>The latest version changes all that. Photos are now big and bold, text is much more readable, and scrolling is <a href="https://www.engadget.com/2012/06/27/project-butter-improves-android-4-1s-speed/">buttery</a> smooth.</p>  <p>If you're one of the many folks who bought a Nexus 7 and are annoyed by how few apps take advantage of it, give <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.sepialabs.glassboard">the latest version of Glassboard</a> a try. It's a much better experience than before.</p>  <p>&#160;</p>  <p><a title="[Click to enlarge]" href="https://nick.typepad.com/images/gb22/nexus7.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto" border="0" src="https://nick.typepad.com/images/gb22/nexus7_sm.png" /></a></p>
